  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,4,"It has been called by some the greatest short story ever told.Since it has been translated into thousands of languages across the world, it is quite possible that during the past two millennia, the sun has not set without the story being referenced somewhere in the world."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,5,"It was told by Jesus Christ, our Savior and Redeemer, who came to earth “to save that which was lost.”He begins with these simple words: “A certain man had two sons.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,6,Immediately we learn of a heartbreaking conflict. One sontells his father he is through with life at home. He wants his freedom. He wants to leave behind the culture and teachings of his parents. He asks for his share of the inheritance—now.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,7,Can you imagine what the father felt when he heard this? When he realized that what his son wanted more than anything else was to leave the family and perhaps never return?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,8,"The son must have felt a thrill of adventure and excitement. At long last, he was on his own. Free from the principles and rules of the culture of his youth, he could finally make his own choices without being influenced by his parents. No more guilt. He could bask in the acceptance of a like-minded community and live life on his own terms."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,9,"Arriving in a faraway country, he quickly made new friends and began living the life he had always dreamed of. He must have been a favorite of many, for he spent money freely. His new friends—beneficiaries of his prodigality—did not judge him. They celebrated, applauded, and championed his choices."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,10,"Had there been social media in that time, surely he would have filled pages with animated photos of laughing friends: #Livingmybestlife! #Neverhappier! #Shouldhavedonethislongago!"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,11,"But the party did not last—it rarely does. Two things happened: first, he ran out of money, and second, a famine swept through the land."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,12,"As the problems worsened, he panicked. The once unstoppable, jubilant high roller now could not afford a single meal, let alone a place to stay. How would he survive?"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,13,He had been generous to his friends—would they help him now? I can see him asking for a little support—just for now—until he got back on his feet.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,14,"The scriptures tell us, “No man gave unto him.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,15,"Desperate to remain alive, he found a local farmer who hired him to feed swine."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,16,"Extremely hungry now, abandoned and alone, the young man must have wondered how things could have gone so terribly, dreadfully wrong."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,17,"It wasn’t just an empty stomach that troubled him. It was an empty soul. He had been so sure that giving in to his worldly desires would make him happy, that moral laws were obstacles to that happiness. Now he knew better. And oh, what a price he had to pay for that knowledge!"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,18,"As the physical and spiritualhunger grew, his thoughts returned to his father. Would he help him after all that had happened? Even the humblest of his father’s servants had food to eat and shelter from the storms."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,19,But return to his father?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,20,Never.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,21,Confess to his village that he had squandered his inheritance?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,22,Impossible.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,23,Face the neighbors who surely had warned him that he was disgracing his family and breaking his parents’ hearts? Return to his old friends after boasting of how he was breaking free?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,24,Unbearable.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,25,"But the hunger, loneliness, and remorse simply wouldn’t go away—until “he came to himself.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,26,He knew what he needed to do.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,27,"Now let us go back to the father, the brokenhearted master of the house. How many hundreds, perhaps thousands, of hours had he spent worrying about his son?"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,28,"How many times had he looked down the very road his son had taken and relived the penetrating loss he had felt as his son walked away? How many prayers had he offered in the deep of night, pleading with God that his son would be safe, that he would discover truth, that he would return?"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,29,"And then one day, the father looks out on that lonely road—the road that leads home—and sees a distant figure walking toward him."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,30,Is it possible?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,31,"Though the individual is a great way off, the father knows in an instant it is his son."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,32,"He runs to him, throws his arms around him, and kisses him."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,33,"“Father,” the son cries out, in words he must have rehearsed a thousand times, “I have sinned against both heaven and you. I am no longer worthy to be called your son. All I ask is that you take me in as a hired servant.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,34,"But the father scarcely lets him finish. Tears in his eyes, he commands his servants: “Bring the finest robe in the house and place it on my son’s shoulders. Put a ring on his finger and sandals on his feet. Make a feast to celebrate. My son has returned!”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,35,In my office hangs a painting by the German artist Richard Burde. Harriet and I love this painting. It depicts one tender scene from the Savior’s parable in a deeper perspective.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,36,"While almost everyone is overjoyed at the son’s return, one is not—his older brother."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,37,He is carrying some emotional baggage.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,38,He was there when his brother demanded his inheritance. He witnessed firsthand the massive weight of grief on his father.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,39,"Ever since his brother left, he has tried to lift his father’s burden. Every day, he has worked to restore his father’s broken heart."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,40,"And now the reckless child is back, and people can’t stop lavishing attention on his rebellious brother."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,41,"“All these years,” he tells his father, “never once have I refused to do a single thing you asked. Yet in all that time, you never celebrated me.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,42,"The loving father responds, “Dear son, all that I have is yours! This is not about comparing rewards or celebrations. This is about healing. This is the moment we have been hoping for all these years. Your brother was dead and is alive again! He was lost but now he is found!”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,43,"My beloved brothers and sisters, dear friends, like all of the Savior’s parables, this one is not just about people living long ago. It’s about you and me, today."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,44,"Who among us has not departed from the path of holiness, foolishly thinking we could find more happiness going our own self-centered way?"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,45,"Who among us has not felt humbled, brokenhearted, and desperate for forgiveness and mercy?"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,46,"Perhaps some may even have wondered, “Is it even possible to go back? Will I be labeled forever, rejected, and avoided by my former friends? Is it better to just stay lost? How will God react if I try to return?”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,47,This parable gives us the answer.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,48,"Our Heavenly Father will run to us, His heart overflowing with love and compassion. He will embrace us; place a robe around our shoulders, a ring on our finger, and sandals on our feet; and proclaim, “Today we celebrate! For my child, who once was dead, has come back to life!”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,49,Heaven will rejoice at our return.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,50,May I take a moment now and speak to you individually?
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,51,"No matter what may have happened in your life, I echo and proclaim the words of my beloved friend and fellow Apostle Elder Jeffrey R. Holland: “It is not possible for you to sink lower than the infinite light of Christ’s [atoning sacrifice] shines.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,52,"Though choices may have taken you far away from the Savior and His Church, the Master Healer stands at the road that leads home, welcoming you. And we as members of the Church of Jesus Christ seek to follow His example and embrace you as our brothers and sisters, as our friends. We rejoice and celebrate with you."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,53,"Your return will not diminish the blessings of others. For the Father’s bounty is infinite, and what is given to one does not in the slightest diminish the birthright of others."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,54,"I do not pretend that coming back is an easy thing to do. I can testify of that. It may, in fact, be the toughest choice you will ever make."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,55,"But I bear witness that the moment you decide to return and walk in the way of our Savior and Redeemer, His power will enter your life and transform it."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,56,Angels in heaven will rejoice.
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,57,"And so will we, your family in Christ. After all, we know what it’s like to be a prodigal. We all rely daily on the same atoning power of Christ. We know this path, and we will walk with you."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,58,"No, our path will not be free from grief, sorrow, or sadness. But we came this far “by the word of Christ with unshaken faith in him, relying wholly upon the merits of him who is mighty to save.” And together we will “press forward with a steadfastness in Christ, having a perfect brightness of hope, and a love of God and of all [people].”Together we will “rejoice with joy unspeakable and full of glory,”for Jesus Christ is our strength!"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,59,"It is my prayer that each one of us may hear, in this profound parable, the Father’s voice calling us to enter the road that leads home—that we may have the courage to repent, receive forgiveness, and follow the path that leads back to our compassionate and merciful God. Of this I bear witness and leave you my blessing in the name of Jesus Christ, amen."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,60,Notes
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,61,"Found inLuke 15, the parable is one of three (the lost sheep, the lost coin, and the lost son) that illustrate the value of lost things and the celebration that occurs when that which was lost is found."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,62,"Luke 19:10."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,63,"Luke 15:11."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,64,"This son was probably young. He was unmarried, which may be an indication of his youth, but not so young that he wasn’t able to demand his inheritance and leave home once he had obtained it."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,65,"By Jewish law and tradition, the older of two sons was entitled to a two-thirds portion of the father’s inheritance. The younger son, therefore, was entitled to a one-third portion. (SeeDeuteronomy 21:17.)"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,66,"SeeLuke 15:13."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,67,"SeeLuke 15:14."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,68,"Luke 15:16."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,69,"To the Jews, pigs were considered “unclean” (seeDeuteronomy 14:8) and were offensive. Practicing Jews would not have raised swine, which indicates the overseer was a Gentile. It could also suggest how far the young son had traveled to be away from practicing Jews."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,70,"Elder Neal A. Maxwell taught: “Of course, it is better if we are humbled ‘because of the word’ rather than being [humbled] by circumstances, yet the latter may do! (seeAlma 32:13–14). Famine can induce spiritual hunger” (“The Tugs and Pulls of the World,”Ensign, Nov. 2000, 36;Liahona, Jan. 2001, 45)."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,71,"Luke 15:17."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,72,"SeeLuke 15:20."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,73,"SeeLuke 15:18–19, 21."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,74,"SeeLuke 15:22–24."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,75,"Remember, the younger son had already received his inheritance. For the older one, that meant that everything else belonged to him. Giving anything to the younger son would mean to take it away from the son who stayed."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,76,"SeeLuke 15:29."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,77,"SeeLuke 15:31–32."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,78,"Jeffrey R. Holland, “The Laborers in the Vineyard,”EnsignorLiahona, May 2012, 33."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,79,"What is given to one does not in the slightest diminish the birthright of others. The Savior taught this doctrine when He offered the parable of the laborers inMatthew 20:1–16."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,80,"SeeAlma 34:31."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,81,"2 Nephi 31:19–20."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,82,"1 Peter 1:8."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/45uchtdorf,Elder Dieter F. Uchtdorf,83,"SeePsalm 28:7."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,4,"From 1856 to 1860, thousands of Latter-day Saint pioneers pulled their belongings in handcarts for over 1,000 miles (1,600 km) as they traveled to the Salt Lake Valley. One hundred sixty-seven years ago this very week, on October 4, 1856, President Brigham Young was surprised to learn that two handcart companies, led by Edward Martin and James Willie, were still hundreds of miles from Salt Lake, with winter fast approaching.The very next day, not far from where we meet today, President Young stood before the Saints and declared: “Many of our brethren and sisters are on the plains with hand-carts, and they must be brought here. … Go and bring in those people now on the plains.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,5,"Just two days later, the first rescue parties departed in search of the handcart pioneers."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,6,"A member of the Willie company described the desperate situation prior to the arrival of the main rescue team. He shared: “[Just] when it seemed all would be lost, … and there seemed little left to live for, like a thunderbolt out of the clear sky, God answered our prayers. A rescue party, bringing food and supplies … , came into sight. … How we thanked God for our rescue.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,7,"These rescuers were heroes to the pioneers, putting their own lives at risk in extreme weather conditions to bring as many as possible safely home. One such hero was Ephraim Hanks."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,8,"In mid-October, and unaware of the handcart predicament, Hanks was returning to his home in Salt Lake following a trip when, during the night, he was awakened by a voice saying, “The hand-cart people are in trouble and you are wanted; will you go and help them?”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,9,"With that question ringing in his mind, he hurried back to Salt Lake City. And upon hearing President Heber C. Kimball call for additional volunteers, Hanks set out the verynext day, on his own, to the rescue. Moving quickly, he overtook other rescuers en route, and upon reaching the Martin company, Hanks recalled, “The sight that met my gaze as I entered their camp can never be erased from my memory … [and] was enough to touch the stoutest heart.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,10,"Ephraim Hanks spent days moving from tent to tent blessing the sick. He related that “in scores of instances, when we administered to the sick, and rebuked the diseases in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ, the sufferers would rally at once; they were healed almost instantly.”Ephraim Hanks will forever be a hero to those handcart pioneers."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,11,"Similar to that remarkable rescue, events which impact our lives and even the course of history are frequently the result of decisions and achievements of individual men and women—great artists, scientists, business leaders, and politicians. These extraordinary individuals are often honored as heroes, with monuments and memorials built to commemorate their exploits."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,12,"When I was a young boy, my first heroes were athletes. My earliest memories are of collecting baseball cards with the pictures and statistics of Major League Baseball players. “Hero worship” as a child can be fun and innocent, as when children dress up as their favorite superheroes for Halloween. Although we admire and respect many talented and remarkable men and women for their abilities and contributions, the degree to which they are revered, if taken to an excess, can be the equivalent of the children of Israel worshipping a golden calf in the desert of Sinai."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,13,"As adults, what was once innocent childhood fun can become a stumbling block when “hero worship” of politicians, bloggers, influencers, athletes, or musicians causes us to look “beyond the mark”and lose sight of what is truly essential."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,14,"For the children of Israel, the challenge was not the gold that they brought with them on their journey to the promised land but rather what they allowed the gold to become: an idol, which then became the object of their worship, turning their attention away from Jehovah, who had parted the Red Sea and delivered them from bondage. Their focus on the calf impacted their ability to worship the true God."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,15,"Thehero—our hero, now and always—is Jesus Christ, and anything or anyone that distracts us from His teachings, as found in the scriptures and through the words of livingprophets, can negatively impact our progress on the covenant path. Before the Creation of this world, we looked to Jesus Christ when it became clear that the plan proposed by Father in Heaven, which included our opportunity to progress and become like Him, was being challenged."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,16,"Not only was Jesus Christ the leader in defending our Father’s plan, but He would also play the most crucial role in its implementation. He responded to the Father and volunteered to offer Himself “a ransom for all,”to pay a debt that each of us would incur through sin but could not pay on our own."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,17,"President Dallin H. Oaks has taught, “[Jesus Christ] has done everything that is essential for our journey through mortality toward the destiny outlined in the plan of our Heavenly Father.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,18,"In the Garden of Gethsemane, when faced with such an overwhelming task, the Savior bravely stated, “Not my will, but thine, be done,” and proceeded to take upon Himself the combined pains, the sicknesses, and the suffering for the sins of all who would ever live.In a perfect act of obedience and commitment, Jesus Christ completedthesupreme heroic act in all of creation, culminating in His glorious Resurrection."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,19,"In our most recent general conference, President Russell M. Nelson reminded us: “Whatever questions or problems you have, the answer is always found in the life and teachings of Jesus Christ. Learn more about His Atonement, His love, His mercy, His doctrine, and His restored gospel of healing and progression. Turn to Him! Follow Him!”And I would add, “Choose Him.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,20,"In our complex world, it can be tempting to turn to society’s heroes in an effort to provide clarity to life when it may seem confusing or overwhelming. We buy the clothes they sponsor, we embrace the politics they espouse, and we follow their suggestions shared on social media. This might be fine for a temporary diversion, but we must be watchful that this form of hero worship does not become our golden calf. Choosing the right hero has eternal consequences."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,21,"When our family arrived in Spain to begin our service as mission leaders, we found a framed quote shared by Elder Neal A. Maxwell that has relevance to the heroes we choose to follow. He stated, “If you have not chosen the kingdom of God first, it will in the end make no difference what you have chosen instead.”Brothers and sisters, it is by choosing Jesus Christ, the King of kings, that we choose the kingdom of God.Anyother choice is the equivalent of choosing the arm of flesh, or a golden calf, and will ultimately fail us."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,22,"In the Old Testament book of Daniel, we read the account of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abed-nego, who clearly knew which hero to choose—and it was not any of the gods of King Nebuchadnezzar. They confidently declared:"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,23,“Our God whom we serve is able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace. …
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,24,"“But if not, be it known unto thee, O king, that we will not serve thy gods, nor worship the golden image.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,25,"As the Apostle Paul taught, “There be gods many,”and, I may add, heroes many to whom we are invited to bow down, to worship, and to embrace. But just as Daniel’s three friends knew, there is only One who is guaranteed to deliver—because He already has and He always will."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,26,"For us on our journey back to the presence of God, to our promised land, it’s not the politician, the musician, the athlete, or the vlogger that is the issue but, rather, choosing to allow them to become the primary objects of our attention and focus in place of our Savior and Redeemer."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,27,"We choose Him, Jesus Christ, when we choose to honor His day whether we’re at home or traveling on vacation. We choose Him when we choose His words through the scriptures and the teachings of living prophets. We choose Him when we choose to hold a temple recommend and live worthy of its use. We choose Him when we are peacemakers and refuse to be contentious, “especiallywhen we have differences of opinion.”"
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,28,"No leader has ever shown more courage, no humanitarian has shownmore kindness, no physician has cured more disease, and no artist has been more creative than Jesus Christ."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,29,"In a world of heroes, with monuments and museums devoted to the exploits of mortal men and women, there is One who stands above all others. I testify that Jesus Christ is not only our hero; He is our Lord and King, the Savior and Redeemer of mankind. In the name of Jesus Christ, amen."
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,30,Notes
  2023,"10",/general-conference/2023/10/46waddell,Bishop W. Christopher Waddell,31,"Studies devoted to the Willie and Martin handcart companies include LeRoy R. and Ann W. Hafen,Handcarts to Zion: The Story of a Unique Western Migration, 1856–1860(1960); Rebecca Cornwall and Leonard J. Arrington,Rescue of the 1856 Handcart Companies(1981); Howard K. and Cory W. Bangerter,Tragedy and Triumph: Your Guide to the Rescue of the 1856 Willie and Martin Handcart Companies, 2nd ed. (2006); and Andrew D. Olsen,The Price We Paid: The Extraordinary Story of the Willie and Martin Handcart Pioneers(2006)."
